'''Sébastien Serge Louis Desabre''' (born 2 August 1976) is a French professional [[association football|football]] [[manager (association football)|manager]],<ref name=3R>{{cite web |url=https://www.florsport.co.ke/african-football/uganda-demanding-100000-compensation-if-egyptian-side-al-ahly-takes-coach-desabre/ |title=Uganda demanding $100,000 compensation if Egyptian side Al Ahly takes coach Desabre |date=28 June 2019 | publisher=Florsport.co.ke |access-date=7 July 2019 | author=Michael Smith Mugote |location=Nairobi}}</ref> currently with [[DR Congo national football team]].

Nicknamed ''The Florist''<ref name=3R/> he served as manager of the [[Uganda national football team|Uganda national team]] from 28 December 2017<ref name="4R">{{cite web|title=New dawn as Desabre appointed Uganda Cranes coach |newspaper=[[Daily Nation]] |date=28 December 2017 | url=https://www.nation.co.ke/sports/football/Sebastien-Desabre-appointed-Uganda-Cranes-coach/1102-4244450-se2mkhz/index.html | access-date=7 July 2019 |author=Denis Bbosa |place=Nairobi}}</ref> until 7 July 2019.<ref name="2R"/>

==Managerial career==
Desabre was born in [[Valence (city)|Valence]].<ref name="4R"/> His past managerial jobs include ES Cannet-Rocheville, [[ASEC Mimosas]], [[Coton Sport FC de Garoua|Coton Sport]] and [[Espérance Sportive de Tunis|Espérance de Tunis]]. He was also head coach of [[Ismaily SC]] in the [[Egyptian Premier League]].<ref name="4R"/> He has also coached [[C.R.D. Libolo|Recreativo do Libolo]], [[Dubai CSC|Dubai Club]], [[JS Saoura]] and [[Wydad AC]].<ref name="4R"/><ref name="5R">{{cite web |url=https://www.kawowo.com/2017/12/28/sebastien-desabre-arrives-uganda-cranes-job/ |title=Sebastien Desabre arrives in Uganda ahead of Cranes unveiling |publisher=Kawowo.com |date=28 December 2017 |access-date=28 December 2017 |author=David Isabirye | location=Kampala}}</ref>

In December 2017, prior to the 2018 [[African Nations Championship]] competition, he signed a multiple-year contract with the [[Federation of Uganda Football Associations]] to manage the [[Uganda national football team|Uganda national team]] at a gross monthly salary of $25,000.<ref name="6R">{{cite web| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42501500|title=Uganda unveil Fenchman Sebastien Desabre as new coach|date=28 December 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=29 August 2019}}</ref><ref name="7R">{{cite web| url=https://www.kawowo.com/2017/12/28/frenchman-desabre-replaces-micho-as-uganda-cranes-head-coach/ |title=Frenchman Desabre replaces Micho as Uganda Cranes head coach |publisher=Kawowo.com |date=28 December 2017 |access-date=28 December 2017 |author=David Isabirye |place=Kampala}}</ref><ref name="8R">{{cite web| url=http://observer.ug/sports/56493-sebastien-desabre-takes-over-cranes-job.html |title=Frenchman takes Cranes job |date=28 December 2017 |access-date=28 December 2017 |author=Uganda Radio Network |author-link=Uganda Radio Network | newspaper=[[The Observer (Uganda)]] quoting Uganda Radio Network| location=Kampala}}</ref> He replaced [[Milutin Sredojević]], who left in July 2017 to become coach of the [[Orlando Pirates F.C.|Orlando Pirates]].<ref name="4R"/> On 17 November 2018, the Cranes qualified for the 2019 African Cup of Nations after defeating [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]].<ref name="9R">{{cite news |url=https://observer.ug/news/headlines/59214-uganda-qualifies-for-afcon-2019 |title=Uganda qualifies for AFCON 2019 |newspaper=The Observer (Uganda) |date=17 November 2018 |
access-date=7 July 2019 |author=Nicholas Bamulanzeki |
place=Kampala}}</ref> In November 2018, the Uganda national team was nominated with five others for the CAF Men's national team of the year award 2018.<ref name="10R">{{cite news |date=30 November 2019 |url=https://futaa.comfutaa.com/zm/article/168619/caf-awards-uganda-kenya-nominated-for-best-national-team-of-the-year-award |title=CAF Awards: Uganda, Kenya nominated for best national team of the year award |publisher=Futaa.com |access-date=7 July 2019 |place=Nairobi}}</ref>

Uganda qualified for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] from 21 June until 19 July 2019. The team advanced out of Group A, to the round of 16, in second position, behind group leader and tournament hosts, [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]]. However, the team was eliminated after losing 1–0 to [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] on 5 July 2019.<ref name="11R">{{cite web| url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Sports/Soccer/Uganda-Cranes-team-returns-home-today--Kiiza-Sebastien-Desabre/690266-5186572-30elllz/index.html |title=Uganda Cranes team returns home | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] quoting Uganda Radio Network |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |author=Uganda Radio Network |place=Kampala}}</ref> The following day, in a statement released by FUFA in Kampala, Desabre's contract with the Cranes was terminated by mutual consent despite the success.<ref name="1R"/><ref name="12R">{{cite web|url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Sports/Soccer/Uganda-Cranes-coach-Desabre-sacked-Egypt-Senegal/690266-5186234-m8upw2/index.html | title=Cranes coach Desabre, FUFA part ways | newspaper=Daily Monitor |date=7 July 2019 |access-date=7 July 2019 |author=Monitor Reporter |place=Kampala}}</ref>

On 8 July 2019, Desabre was announced as the new head coach of the Egyptian Premier League club [[Pyramids FC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48914917|title=Sebastien Desabre: Former Uganda coach joins Pyramids in Egypt|date=8 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=29 August 2019|author=Nick Cavell}}</ref> On 19 January 2020, Desabre rejoined [[Wydad AC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingfut.com/2020/01/19/wydad-casablanca-appoint-sebastien-desabre/|title=Wydad Casablanca appoint Sébastien Desabre|website=kingfut.com|date=19 January 2020}}</ref>

In 2022, he was appointed coach of [[DR Congo national football team]], replacing the Argentine [[Héctor Cúper]], after DR Congo failed to qualify for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. His contract was signed for four years, with the aim of guiding DR Congo to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/africa/62463991 | title=Desabre named as new coach of DR Congo | work=BBC Sport | date=8 August 2022 }}</ref> During the 2026 World Cup qualification, DR Congo defeated both [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|second round]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/fifa-world-cup/news/dr-congo-edge-nigeria-on-penalties-to-reach-inter-confederation-play-off/ |title=DR Congo edge Nigeria on penalties to reach inter-confederation play-off |publisher=CAF Online |date=16 November 2025 }}</ref> before achieving a 1–0 extra-time win over [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-offs]] to secure their second World Cup appearance after 1974.<ref>{{cite web |last=Williams |first=Ian |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cn43qqy9z8xo |title=Tuanzebe sends DR Congo back to World Cup after 52 years |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2026 }}</ref>

